{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564020"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:08:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:08:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16926"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16926"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.4,0.18,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9616"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67768"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9616"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53233"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3819"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22696"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67768"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of bright red rectal bleeding and anal pain. She reports occasional mucous discharge and difficulty with defaecation. She has lost three kilograms in weight over this period. She has a history of HIV infection diagnosed eight years ago and is compliant with antiretroviral therapy. Her CD4 count is stable. She does not take any other regular medications. She is a current smoker with a 30 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Digital rectal examination reveals a firm, tender mass at the anal verge. Proctoscopy confirms a 3 cm ulcerated lesion in the anal canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA biopsy is performed and histopathology shows malignant cells arranged in nests and sheets with moderate nuclear pleomorphism, prominent nucleoli, and frequent mitoses. Several concentric whorls of flattened cells are present within the tumour nests.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histological findings is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Signet ring cells","Keratin pearls","Psammoma bodies","Reed-Sternberg cells","Reinke crystals"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological description in the stem is classic for squamous cell carcinoma. The presence of malignant cells arranged in nests with nuclear pleomorphism and mitoses suggests a carcinoma, while the description of concentric whorls of flattened cells suggests squamous differentiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratin pearls\u003C/strong\u003E are concentrically laminated masses of keratin formed by well to moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinomas. They represent attempted terminal differentiation of the malignant squamous cells and are a characteristic diagnostic feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESignet ring cells\u003C/strong\u003E are typically seen in adenocarcinomas, particularly those of gastric origin. They contain abundant intracellular mucin that pushes the nucleus to one side, creating a ring-like appearance. These would not be expected in a squamous cell carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsammoma bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are concentrically laminated calcified structures typically found in papillary thyroid carcinoma, meningiomas, and some ovarian tumours. They are not a feature of squamous cell carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReed-Sternberg cells\u003C/strong\u003E are the characteristic cells of classical Hodgkin lymphoma. They are large cells with multiple nuclei or a single nucleus with multiple prominent nucleoli giving an \u0027owl\u0027s eye\u0027 appearance. They would not be seen in carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReinke crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are crystalloids found in Leydig cell tumours of the testis. They are rod-shaped, crystalline structures that are not associated with squamous cell carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["P16 positivity on immunohistochemistry is a surrogate marker for HPV-associated malignancy.","Keratin pearls are a characteristic histological feature of well to moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma.","Squamous cell carcinoma shows malignant cells arranged in nests with nuclear pleomorphism and frequent mitoses."],"references":["Clark MA, Hartley A, Geh JI. Cancer of the anal canal. The Lancet Oncology. 2004 Mar 1;5(3):149\u201357.","Hoff PM, Coudry R, Moniz CMV. Pathology of Anal Cancer. Surgical Oncology Clinics. 2017 Jan 1;26(1):57\u201371."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53233"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16926"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53233"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T22:25:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T22:28:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9616"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67768"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms"